=====================================================
                   The Calculators                   
=====================================================
                                                     
  The calculators project is the way I used to explore
new programming languages, since creating a calculator
requires me to understand the concepts of reading and
writing to stream, error handling and more.

  So in this project I will implement the calculators
in the programming languages I could think of using
the folloeing standards, I would also not use LLM to
write any code for this project is it just for me to
explore.

  Also use this project at your own risk as it could
contain unfinished features and bugs. Your are
welcomed to open any issues about the code on GitHub,
but I will not accept any pull requests changing the
source code.

                      Standards                      

Modes

Each calculator has to contain 2 modes, which is 
determined base on arguments

- Argument mode: Specifies the expression in
  arguments, used when detected there are arguments in 
  `argv`.
- Interactive mode: Expressions are entered after
  program started, or piped to `stdin` of the program. 
  Used when no arguments are added

Tokenization
                                                     
All calculators should support both the expression
being seperated via spaces like `1 + 1 / 2` or the
expression combined like `1+1/2`, which leads to the
need of tokenization when expressions are in combined
mode.

Calculation Order

This calculator supports multi-step expressions
like `1+1/2` where the calculator will first handle
division and then addition. This will be archived
mostly using array lists or other types of compoud
data types.

Variables

Both environment variabls and local variables within
the calculator can be accessed via their names and a
`$` in front.

Standard variables like `pi` should be pre-defined
locally.

History Saving & Keyboard Input Manipulation

All calculations made will be stored in the file
`~/.calchistory`, and this will only be written
until the application will quit. Then if the user
press the up or down arrow keys, the application
will intercept the key stroke and append the
history.

Error Handling

When there are syntax errors or illegal operations
detected, the application will throw an exception 
usually to the programming languages' error handing
system. If none then it will be self handled.

Signal Handling

The calculators should handle `SIGINT` for quitting
the application and write the calc history.

Advanced Mathmatical Operations

The calculators should support a variation of
advanced mathmatical operations such as `sin()`
and `tan()`, the use of the program's mathmatical
library is allowed.

The syntax for these are the same as calling functions
where it will look like `tan(1+2)` in calc.

                  Current Status                     

Languages Implemented

- C++: Most support
- Swift: Intermediate support
- Rust: Intermediate support

Languages Planned

- Java
- C
- Python
